{"questionId":"9069469","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Hydrogen and iodine react to form hydrogen iodide.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">H<sub>2</sub> (g) + <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>I</mtext></math><sub>2</sub> (g) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" class=\"wrs_chemistry\"><mo>⇌</mo></math> 2H<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>I</mtext></math> (g)</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the reaction of hydrogen with solid iodine.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">H<sub>2</sub> (g) + <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>I</mtext></math><sub>2</sub> (s) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" class=\"wrs_chemistry\"><mo>⇌</mo></math> 2H<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>I</mtext></math> (g)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Δ<em>H</em><sup>⦵</sup>&nbsp;= +53.0 kJ mol<sup>−1</sup></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Calculate the entropy change of reaction, Δ<em>S</em><sup>⦵</sup>, in J K<sup>−1</sup> mol<sup>−1</sup>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/c75be767348a53bd027a4e3694f826a1b9a7326b.png\"></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>«Δ<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><msup><mi>S</mi><mo>⦵</mo></msup><mtext>reaction</mtext></msub></math>&nbsp;= 2 × 206.6 – (130.6 + 116.1) =» 166.5 «J K<sup>–1</sup> mol<sup>–1</sup>» ✔</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9069469","referenceCode":"22M.2.hl.TZ2.4d(i)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Calculate the entropy change of reaction, ΔS⦵, in J K−1 mol−1.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d(i)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 15: Energetics/thermochemistry","15.2 Entropy and spontaneity","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 15: Energetics/thermochemistry"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVers